# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: balık-ekmek
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Other akara types includes Akara Awon (from beans and okro) and Egusi Akara (made from egusi seeds).
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Another type of Akara product is Akara Ogbomosho (Akara chips) which are crunchy chips.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Brazilian acarajé is made from raw and milled cowpeas that are seasoned with salt, pepper and chopped onions molded into the shape of a large scone and deep-fried in dendê with a wok-like pan in front of the customers.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] It is served split in half and stuffed with *vatapá* and *caruru* – spicy pastes made from shrimp, ground cashews, palm oil and other ingredients.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] A vegetarian version is typically served with hot peppers and green tomatoes.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé can also comes in a second form called abará, in which the nutritious ingredients are steamed instead of deep-fried, similar to moi moi.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé serves as both a religious offering to the gods in the Candomblé religion and as street food.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] In Sierra Leone, *akara* is composed of rice flour, mashed banana, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] After mixed together, it is dropped in oil by hand, and fried, similar to puff-puff.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] *Akara* is usually prepared for events like Pulnado (event held due to the birth of a child), a wedding, funeral, or party.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé sold on the street in Brazil are variously made with fried beef, mutton, dried shrimp, pigweed, fufu osun sauce, and coconut.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Today in Bahia, Brazil, most street vendors who serve acarajé are women, easily recognizable by their all-white cotton dresses and headscarves and caps.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] They first appeared in Bahia selling acarajé in the 19th century.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Earnings from the sale of acarajé were used both to buy the freedom of enslaved family members until the abolition of slavery in Brazil in 1888; its sale additionally served as a source of family income.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] The city now has more than 500 acarajé vendors.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] The image of these women, often simply called *baianas*, frequently appears in artwork from the region of Bahia.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé, however, is available outside of the state of Bahia as well, including the streets of its neighborboring state of Sergipe, and the markets of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé is essential ritual food used in Afro-Brazilian religious traditions such as Candomblé.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] The first acarajé in a Candomblé ritual is offered to the orixá Exu.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] They vary in size based on their offering to a specific deity: large, round acarajé are offered to Xangô; ones smaller in form are offered to Iansã.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Small, fritter-size acarajé are offered to Erê (deity), or child spirits.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé is used in Candomblé rituals in the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro, São Paulo, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, and Maranhão.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] It is closely related to acaçá, a similar ritual food made of steamed corn mush.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is a variety of acarajé fried in an oil other than palm oil; olive oil or other vegetable oils are generally used.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is used in Candomblé offerings to orixás with a ritual prohibition of the use of palm oil.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] This variety is found in the states of Bahia and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé de Xangô (àkàrà tí Ṣàngó) is a variety of acarajé offered to the orixá Xangô, known as the òriṣà Ṣangó in the Yoruba culture.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] It is made of the same ingredients as the common form but greatly elongated.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] This variety is found on the ritual platter of amalá offered to Xangô.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] This variety is found in the state of Bahia and in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] Acarajé was listed as a national intangible historic heritage (*patrimônio nacional imaterial*), by the National Institute of Historic and Artistic Heritage in 2004; the role of *baianas* in the preparation and sale of acarajé was recognized in the same act.
[src:balık-ekmek/acarajé] In October 2023, Rio de Janeiro declared the fritter to be part of that city's cultural heritage.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-chaat] It can be served as a snack, a side dish or a light meal.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-chaat] It is made from boiled and fried cubed potatoes served with chat masala.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-chaat] It is a versatile dish that has many regional variations.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-chaat] The word *alu* means potatoes in Hindi and the word *chat* is derived from the Hindi word *chatna*, which means 'tasting'.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-chaat] Thus, 'alu chat' means a savory potato snack.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-tikki] Because of the broad geographical distribution of Indian people throughout the world, a number of variations on this dish exist.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-tikki] In Maharashtra, a popular version of aloo tikki is served with a spicy curry and various chutneys.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-tikki] It is called ragda pattice and is sold at various chaat stalls throughout the city and especially on Chowpatti Beach.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-tikki] The aloo tikki in this region is made of mainly locally grown spices such as turmeric, whereas in Bangalore, more coriander is used.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-tikki] In the United Kingdom, vegetable tikki is available from delicatessen counters at various shops.
[src:balık-ekmek/aloo-tikki] Some North Indian dhabas or café-style eateries will sandwich the aloo in bread.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] Anticuchos can be found on street-carts and street food stalls (*anticucheras*).
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] The meat may be marinated in vinegar and spices (such as cumin, ají pepper and garlic).
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] While anticuchos can be made of any type of meat, the most popular are made of beef heart (*anticuchos de corazón*).
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] Anticuchos usually come with a boiled potato at the end of the skewer.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] A similar dish, shish kebab, is found in Mediterranean cuisine.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] In Peru, anticuchos are linked to the procession of Señor de los Milagros.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] In the 16th century European ingredients such as garlic were added and beef began to replace the traditional llama that was used at the time of the Inca Empire.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] It was a popular dish among the inhabitants of the Inca Empire, and it is currently popular throughout most South American countries.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] Americanized versions of anticuchos are sometimes made of non-organ meats.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] According to the text file from the National Library in Lima (Peru), it is believed that the term comes from the Quechua *antikuchu* (*anti*: 'East' + *kuchu*: 'cut' or *uchu*: 'porridge, mix').
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] The writer Erika Fetzer mentions that according to tradition, anticuchos were prepared with meat and flame.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] The Spanish strung the meat on sticks as skewers.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] The Spaniards also brought enslaved Africans, who were concentrated in Lima and the coast of southern Peru of the Vice-royalty of Peru.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] In those days, the Spanish dismissed offal as food for slaves; the Spanish generally cooked with the "prime" cuts only.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] As a result, many traditional recipes use beef heart and other "off" cuts.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] In Peru, the tradition continues with the traditional name and ingredients; anticuchos are consumed by all social classes of Peru, and are especially popular as a street food.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] Traditional anticuchos are made with beef heart slivers ranging from 2 cm x 2 cm to about 5 cm × 5 cm, roasted on a metal skewer about 30 to 40 cm (16 in) long and 3 × 3 mm in diameter.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] They are seasoned with salt to taste, and sometimes with vinegar.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] A popular dressing is a sauce made from garlic, onion, aji panca, cumin, black pepper, and beer, which is spread onto the anticuchos while cooking.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] Anticuchos are usually not the main course of a meal, but rather an accompaniment to grilled meats along with other side dishes such as choripanes, potatoes, sausages and salads.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] Anticuchos are part of traditional Peruvian cuisine.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] The greatest consumption in Peru is in July, during the celebration of *Fiestas Patrias* (Independence Day) in fondas and BBQs.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] The Bolivian anticucho is a dish based on thin beef heart fillets marinated in spices, oil, and vinegar, cooked on skewers and over charcoal, and then served hot, mainly accompanied by roast potatoes and spicy sauce or peanut llajua.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] The anticucho is widely known as one of the favorite night delicacies dishes in innumerable parts of Bolivia.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] The vendors (affectionately known as "anticucheras") are easy to find on streets or boulevards and have a peculiar ritual to attract their clients, which consists of creating spectacular flames of fire that give off the irresistible aroma of the dish.
[src:balık-ekmek/anticucho] Known as "chuzos" in the Sierra Region and "carne en palito" in the Costa Region, they are a favorite night street food.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] The invention has been attributed, though without evidence, to Zuo Zongtang, a military leader of the late Qing dynasty.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] In 1855, the army of the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom invaded the Fujian region and General Zuo was appointed to lead an army to crush the rebels.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] The recipe does seem to have spread throughout the Fujian region, especially around Quanzhou and later on throughout Southeast China.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] It was brought south into Southeast Asia or Nanyang by Hokkien and Teochew immigrants, especially to Singapore, and merchants spread it to neighbouring regions.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] In Indonesia, this dish originated in Bangka Belitung Islands by ethnic Chinese (Hokkien and Khek) and it was named “Hok Lo Pan” which translates to “Hoklo ethnicity’s cake.” Its traditional topping includes sugar and sesame seeds.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] Martabak manis have different names in different regions.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] In West Borneo, it is called *apam pinang*, similar to Malaysia's *apam balik*.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] In Central Java, *martabak manis* is referred to as *kue Bandung* which means Bandung cake.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] The origin of *kue Bandung* started when a man from Bangka Belitung, opened a Martabak manis stall beside a “Bandung Noodle” stall.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] The dessert is also known by various names in different languages, depending on the region.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] The pancake's batter is made from a mixture of flour, eggs, sugar, baking soda, coconut milk and water.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] The batter is cooked upon a thick round iron frying pan in plenty of palm margarine to avoid it sticking to the pan.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] Then other ingredients are sprinkled as filling; the most common or traditional is crushed peanut granules with sugar and sweetcorn kernels (available from cans), but modern innovations such as chocolate sprinkles and cheddar cheese are also available.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] Then, the pancake is folded (hence the name: "turnover pancake") and cut into several pieces.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] In Indonesia there is a smaller version made with smaller pan, they are called *martabak mini* or *terang bulan mini*.
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] The texture of the apam balik can vary depending on the amount of batter and type of pan used, from one that is akin to a crispier form of crumpets to small thin light pancake shells that break when bitten (the latter is usually called *apam balik nipis*, 'thin apam balik').
[src:balık-ekmek/apam-balik] There is a Peranakan variant, the *apom balik*, that closely resembles the Indonesian *Serabi*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] A number of regional variants exist which differ in their fillings and shape.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] *Arancini al ragù* produced in eastern Sicily, particularly in cities such as Catania and Messina, have a conical shape inspired by the volcano Etna.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] In Sicilian, *arancini* is grammatically plural.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] The corresponding singular is either the masculine *arancinu* or the feminine *arancina*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] The eastern side of Sicily tends to use the masculine form, while the western side tends to use the feminine form.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] In Italian, the masculine *arancino* (pl.: *arancini*) form has become prevalent, although the feminine form *arancina* (pl.: *arancine*) can also be used.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] Arancini are said to have originated in 10th-century Sicily, at a time when the island was under Arab rule.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] Academic Annette Condello pinpoints arancini's origin to 18th-century southern Italy, where she says it was made to resemble oranges.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] In the cities of Palermo, Syracuse, and Trapani in Sicily, arancini are a traditional food for the feast of Saint Lucy (Italian: *Santa Lucia*) on 13 December, when bread and pasta are not eaten.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] This commemorates the arrival of a grain supply ship on Saint Lucy's Day in 1646, relieving a severe famine.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] Today, with the increasing popularity of this finger food in Italy, arancini are found all year round at most Sicilian food outlets.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] The most common type of arancini sold in Sicilian cafés is *arancini cû sucu* (transl.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] *arancini al ragù*), which typically consists of meat in a tomato sauce, rice, and mozzarella or other cheese.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] Many cafés also offer *arancini cû burru* (transl.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] *arancini al burro*, with butter or béchamel sauce) or specialty arancini, such as *arancini chî funci* (transl.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] *arancini ai funghi*, with mushrooms), *arancini câ fastuca* (transl.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] *arancini al pistacchio*, with pistachios), or *arancini â norma* (transl.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] In Roman cuisine, *supplì* are similar, but are commonly filled with cheese (different preparation methods and filling distribution).
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] In Naples, rice balls are called *pall' 'e riso*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] They are smaller than Sicilian arancini, and are not necessarily filled.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] In Italian literature, Inspector Montalbano, the main character of Andrea Camilleri's detective novels, is a well-known lover of arancini—especially those made by Adelina Cirrinciò, his housekeeper and cook.
[src:balık-ekmek/arancini] The success of the book series and the television adaptation has contributed to making this dish known outside of Italy.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Arepa can be served with accompaniments, such as cheese, *cuajada*, various types of meat, avocado, or *diablito* (deviled ham spread).
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] It can also be split to make sandwiches.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Sizes, maize types, and added ingredients vary based on preparation.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] It is similar to the Mexican *gordita,* the Salvadoran pupusa, the Ecuadorian *tortilla de maíz*, and the Panamanian *tortilla* or *changa*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The *arepa* is a pre-Columbian dish from the area that is now Colombia, Panama and Venezuela.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Instruments used to make flour for the *arepas*, and the clay slabs on which they were cooked, were often found at archaeological sites in the area.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Although it has not been specified in which country an **arepa** was cooked for the first time, it has been possible to define the oldest dates of the presence of maize in Colombia and Venezuela.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] For example, in Colombia, the first record of the presence of corn cultivation dates from about 6,000 years ago.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] However, the presence of arepas dates from 3,000 years ago (specifically in the Altiplano Cundiboyacense by the Muisca), while in Venezuela, the estimate is about 2,800 years ago.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Throughout its history, the **arepa** has stayed mainly unchanged from the **arepas** that pre-Columbian native peoples would have consumed, making the **arepa** one of the few pre-contact traditions that have remained popular in the years since colonization.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The name **arepa** is related to *erepa*, the word for 'cornbread' in the Cumanagoto language.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The **arepa** is a flat, round, unleavened patty of soaked, ground kernels of maize, or—more frequently nowadays—maize meal or maize flour.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] It can be grilled, baked, fried, boiled, or steamed.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The characteristics vary by color, flavor, size, and the food with which it may be stuffed, depending on the region.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Simple **arepas** are filled with butter or cheese and baked.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Depending on the meal, more filling varieties can be added with combinations of ingredients like beans, meat, avocados, eggs, tomatoes, salad, shrimp, or fish.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Fried **arepas** are often consumed in northern South America, filled with white cheese on top and served with fried eggs.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Sweet fried **arepas** are another variety often prepared with sugarloaf (*papelón*) and anise (*anís*).
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Venezuelan white cheese is another topping for fried *arepas* that can be combined with feta cheese.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Initially, *arepa* flour was made by grinding maize at home.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In the 1950s, precooked *arepa* flour was invented by Dr.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Luis Caballero Mejías, a Venezuelan engineer, and became an instant success.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The flour is mixed with water and salt, and occasionally oil, butter, eggs or milk.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Because the flour is already cooked, the blend forms into patties easily.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] After being kneaded and formed, the patties are fried, grilled, or baked.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Some varieties of *arepas* are made with "peeled" corn using the nixtamalization process; they are known as *arepa pelada*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] However, in countries such as Colombia, it is not common to reconstitute corn flour as it is in Venezuela.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Thus, in Colombia, it is more common to see pre-roasted arepas ready for consumption in stores and supermarkets, giving rise to an industry that in 2019 alone had sales of USD $124 million with companies such as Arepas Sary and Alpina Productos Alimenticios.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] According to food anthropologist Ocarina Castillo of the Central University of Venezuela, the dish is likely thousands of years old and originated in the region now occupied by the two countries before colonizers of the area drew borders.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] There are different ways to prepare *arepas*, but one of the most traditional is the Cotoca recipe.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Several varieties of *arepa* can be found in the country, such as the Cruceña and Andina varieties.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The first record of the existence of arepas dates from about 3,000 years ago in what is currently Colombia.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The *arepa* is an iconic food in Colombia, with some 75 distinct preparation forms.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] According to a study conducted by the Colombian Academy of Gastronomy, the *arepa* is part of the Colombian cultural heritage and can be considered a symbol of national gastronomic unity.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In 2006, the *arepa* was named the cultural symbol of Colombia in a competition organized by *Semana* magazine with support from Caracol Televisión, the Ministry of Culture and 'Colombia is Passion'.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In the Paisa region, the *arepa* is especially important to the local people and sometimes accompanies all meals of the day.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In addition, *arepas* are strung into necklaces and placed around the necks of honored dignitaries as a sign of praise.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Many varieties of *arepa* were introduced from this region.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In Colombia, the *arepa* is sold commercially in neighborhood stores, chain supermarkets, and market plazas and packaged with preservatives as a pre-molded white or yellow corn dough ready to grill or fry at home.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] It is also sold in the form of industrialized corn flour that requires hydration before preparation.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In addition, *arepas* are sold by street vendors, in cafeterias, and in neighborhood stores.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Restaurants of the Paisa Region offer a wide variety of *arepas*, including a unique style of stuffed *arepa* that can be filled with eggs, meat, or cheese.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Colombians in the Caribbean region commonly eat a breakfast variation called *arepa con huevo*, which consists of a cooked *arepa* which has been split open, stuffed with a raw egg, and fried.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The Colombian Arepa Festival is celebrated in Barranquilla, Bogotá, Bucaramanga, Cali and Medellín.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Each city takes turns organizing the festival between August and December.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] There are also many other types of arepas, including arepa de choclo, arepa de queso, arepa frita, arepa costeña, arepa de yuca, and arepa paisa.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Some recipes for this type of **arepa** can contain *doble crema* cheese and chicken.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] One of its characteristics is that it is relatively thin unlike other *arepas* and also has a toasted and golden colored shell.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Another variation is the **arepa* boyacense*, with the Municipality of Ventaquemada being one of the most outstanding in terms of its production.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] This type of **arepa** may contain butter, eggs, and cheese.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] It has a certain sweetness, and in some recipes, this **arepa** may have *cuajada*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] There is also the **arepa* paisa*, which is consumed in the Department of Antioquia.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] It is prepared with *maíz trillado* (lit.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] This form most closely resembles indigenous cuisine.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In addition, another **arepa** variation consumed in the Andean region of the country is the **arepa* santandereana*, which contains cooked yuca and *chicharrón*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In the Province of Guanacaste, **arepas** are prepared in the form of large, toasted sponge cakes, seasoned with *Bagaces* type cheese.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In Cartago, during colonial times, *arepas* were filled with pork.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In Puerto Rico, mainly in the San Juan area and beach sides, *arepas* are popular.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] They can also be found in some restaurants, almost always as *arepas de coco*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The Puerto Rican *arepa* is made with wheat flour, coconut milk, coconut oil, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] They can be fried, baked, or cooked on a grill.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Once done, the *arepa* is cut open and stuffed.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Crab, shrimp, and octopus stewed in sofrito, lemon, coconut milk, and ginger, among other ingredients, are the most popular.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The arepa is a symbol of Venezuelan gastronomy and one of the most common pre-Hispanic foods still popular in Venezuela.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The first records of this dish are about 2,800 years ago.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] According to a 2015 survey of the Venezuelan people, nearly 70 percent of the nation ate **arepas** regularly.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] It is common for Venezuelans to eat **arepas** throughout the day, both as snacks and as sides to meals, creating a culture where these corn products (Harina PAN) can be found almost everywhere and in specific restaurants called *areperas*.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] The **arepa** is seen as a cornerstone of a Venezuelan diet; prior to the 2015 food shortages, it was estimated that each year the average Venezuelan consumed about 30 kilos of the corn flour used to make **arepas**.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Venezuelan *arepas* are commonly filled with a great variety of different fillings, from beef and avocado to cheese, varying widely by the location of where they are sold and the ingredients that can be obtained.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] In Venezuela's Andes region, *arepas de trigo* are made with wheat flour rather than cornmeal.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] These lighter **arepas** are generally eaten as a snack or an accompaniment to heavier meals.
[src:balık-ekmek/arepa] Former Venezuelan president Nicolás Maduro "has tried to use arepas as a nationalist rallying point, if not a political tool, claiming the food is from his country alone", according to the *New York Times*.
[src:balık-ekmek/balık-ekmek] The name is a combination of the Turkish words *balık* 'fish' and *ekmek* 'bread'.
